   >trouble and/or the evidence acquired is tainted.....

   They do. It's called a warrant.

More or less true, though you can't always get access to warrants,
and sometimes you need to know the details of the warrant before you
can ask for it successfully.  On the other hand, illegal wiretaps
aren't (generally) usable in court; somebody once posted that the
official term that makes it ok to use is "we got an anonymous tip that ..."
